cmCourseInfo.description: This course is a mandatory component of the Arts & Science Internship Program (ASIP) for students admitted to the ASIP stream of their program for Year 2, and students admitted for Year 2 must successfully complete this course and receive a passing grade to gain access to the ASIP job board. The course will provide an opportunity for students to prepare for and maximize their learning and personal development through ASIP. Topics may include: self-assessment – skills, values, interests; building a career and co-op plan; skills articulation – how to identify, articulate and apply skills gained through courses and other life experiences; personal marketing documents; guided self-reflection on barriers to employment; resources and toolkits to support access for all; and co-op student panels. This course does not carry credit weight and is evaluated as Credit/No Credit. No tuition fee is associated, however an ancillary fee will be assessed. Refer to the ASIP Fees & Financial Aid website for further details. Students who enrolled in the ASIP stream of their program in Year 3 should enrol in PDC230H1.
cmCourseInfo.title: Arts & Science Internship Program - Maximizing Your Experience

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

The PDC220H1 course is available to all Year 2 students enrolled in the Arts & Science Internship Program and will include both synchronous and asynchronous components. Specific synchronous sections will occasionally have some subject matter tailored to specific disciplines. 

The following LEC sections will be tailored to the programs below: 

  • Monday 10am – 11am: Book & Media Studies, Industrial Relations & Human Resources, Pharmacology & Toxicology, and Pharmaceutical Chemistry
  • Wednesday 12pm – 1pm: Computer Science
  • Thursday 3pm – 4pm: Mathematics
  • Thursday 5pm – 6pm: Computer Science and Statistical Science

The synchronous PDC220H1 LEC sections will be taking place bi-weekly starting the week of September 26th, 2022.

Delivery Instructions

This course will have online and in-person synchronous and asynchronous components. It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online programming.

Lecture section options include both online and in-person synchronous delivery formats.

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

The PDC3201H1 course is available to all Year 3 students enrolled in the Arts & Science Internship Program and will include both synchronous and asynchronous components. Specific synchronous sections will occasionally have some subject matter tailored to specific disciplines. 

The following LEC sections will be tailored to the programs below: 

  • Monday 5pm – 6pm: Computer Science and Statistical Science
  • Tuesday 11am – 12pm: Mathematics
  • Wednesday 1pm – 2pm: Book & Media Studies, Industrial Relations & Human Resources, Pharmacology & Toxicology, and Pharmaceutical Chemistry
  • Thursday 1pm – 2pm: Computer Science

The synchronous PDC320H1 LEC sections will be taking place bi-weekly starting the week of September 19th, 2022. 

Delivery Instructions

This course will have online and in-person synchronous and asynchronous components. It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online programming.

Lecture section options include both online and in-person synchronous delivery formats.
